post_text:
Attention Holland CSD Grades 5-12 families‚Ä¶here are the expectations for students for at-home learning days:

1-Each student will receive a daily email to their school email with a link to their required daily check-in. This check-in asks what they are working on that day and how they are doing. This check-in is used to mark them ‚Äúpresent‚Äù or ‚Äúabsent‚Äù for at-home days, which is required by the New York State Education Department. There is not a specific time this needs to be submitted, although it must be completed before the next morning.

2-On at-school days, students will receive independent work for the at-home day, as well as homework from the at-school day. Students should complete that independent work and any remaining homework on their at-home days.

3-Independent work for at-home days will be graded. It is important that students realize this work is a required part of their classes this year and is not optional.

Any questions please contact your building principal

Parents/guardians may submit the COVID-19 Weekly Questionnaire using the following methods:

1) www.hollandcsd.org -> "Quick Links" -> "COVID-19 Student Questionnaire"

2) Go to: www.tinyurl.com/hcsdweeklycheck

3) Scan the QR code. How?

Download a QR app if you do NOT have an iPhone or Pixel phone.

iPhone/Pixel:

1. Open the camera on your phone.

2.Hover over the QR code (Do NOT take a picture):

3. A notification will immediately appear on your phone. It may say something like "Open "forms.office.com" in Safari".

4. Tap on the notification.

5. You will see the Questionnaire.

6. Please complete & submit the Questionnaire one time each week for each student sometime between 6am on Sunday and 6am on Monday.

Contactless Payment Procedures for School lunch:

The food service department is not accepting cash or check payments currently. Payment for school meals will only be funding accepted on www.myschoolbucks.com. Please contact the Food Service Director at (716) 537-8126 with any questions or concerns.

MySchoolBucks
MySchoolBucks is a website for parents to pay for their child's school meals using a credit or debit card. With this online service, parents can also view a child's cafeteria purchases, make payments for their children even if they attend different schools, and set up automatic email reminders to be notified when a payment is needed.
www.myschoolbucks.com

See you soon!

post_text:
The Boys & Girls Club of Holland is considering a before-school Project Learn program for students in grade 2-4 this year if there is enough interest that would assist with staggered elementary school arrival times.

The Program would run Monday-Friday from 8:00 a.m. to 10:00 a.m. on days that school is in session. Parents would need to drop off their child at the Club and a bus would shuttle them to school at 10:00 a.m.

A nominal daily fee will be charged based on the number of participants and staffing requirements. Space will be limited.

Please call the Boys & Girls Club at 537-9370 to inquire, or email Paige Hughes at Paige@BGCHolland.org. In addition the Club will be open from 12:30 p.m. to 6:00 p.m for all students grades 2-8 who physically attended the school that day.
Pre-registration will be required as no drop-in will be allowed, members will be kept in pods of fifteen with the same staff members.

DRAFT REOPENING PLAN RELEASE

Dear Holland Community,
I hope this message finds you well. I would like to inform you that our draft reopening plan (click link below this message) has been submitted to the New York State Education Department and posted here for your review. We involved multiple stakeholders in this challenging endeavor. Please know, the safety of our students and staff are our number one priority. In addition, we are focused on providing a high quality, equitable educational experience to all of our students, while adhering to the requirements that we must follow.

This school year will be different, but we know we are fortunate to have a strong, supportive, community. We look forward to working together to make this transition and meeting the needs of our students, staff, and families. Please stay safe.

Sincerely,

Cathy Fabiatos

Superintendent

post_text:
The pandemic has had a tremendous impact on the operations and production at Life-Touch, Holland's yearbook provider.

The good news is, their yearbook plants are open and printing, but are running on a reduced staff to adhere to social distancing mandates. Their production continues to trend upward, and they are doing their best to maintain a reasonable timeline for yearbook delivery. Although, they are unable to fully commit to a firm date. We will receive tracking information once our year book is ready to ship.

Thank you for your patience.

The survey feedback will be shared with our Reopening Task Force as well as with planning teams within our individual schools.

post_text:
Message from Superintendent Fabiatos regarding Task Force Volunteers 6/23/2020

A School Re-Opening District Task Force has been created. At this time the unknowns far outweigh what is known. Leaders and employees in the field have been consulted to identify a variety of ideas/plans depending on what the future holds. The results of a recent survey of parents was beneficial, however, at this time we hope to add a couple of current parent community members to each of our academic building teams. Please follow the link provided on our district homepage, under "Latest News" to complete a volunteer form if interested. The deadline for submission is Tuesday, June 30th. Volunteers chosen will be notified of meeting dates by Friday, July 3rd. Commitment includes availability for one to two meetings per week, Monday through Friday, between the hours of 9 a.m. and 1 p.m.

post_text:
Dear Students

I hope this message finds you well. First and foremost, we MISS you! Schools were not built to be empty and without students the buildings are not alive. Thank you for your efforts and flexibility in an unusual situation. While the future holds many unknowns I know that our students can be nimble, committed and successful. Best wishes for a safe and enjoyable summer and to our graduates who are pioneers, best wishes for continued success!

Superintendent Fabiatos

post_text:
Dear HCS Families

I hope this message finds you well. While we always appreciate your support we especially want to recognize your dedication during the last three months. While the task was daunting you encouraged and assisted your students to ensure participation, attendance and ultimately their success and it is much appreciated. We do not know what the future holds and there are more unknowns than knowns, but we know that together we will rise to the challenges and be successful. Please continue to refer to the COVID-19 Webpage for updated information. Please also know we make every attempt to get you information as quickly as possible, albeit we often hear news at the same time you are hearing it. Best wishes for good health, safety and a relaxing summer. "See" you in September!

Superintendent Fabiatos

A Message from Superintendent Fabiatos Regarding Changes in Graduation

I hope this message finds you well. A few changes to graduation. Entry to the Delevan Drive-in will begin at 7 p.m. on Friday, June 26th. Diplomas will be conferred by the High School Principal to each student who will be called up front beginning at 8 p.m. The virtual ceremony will begin at 9 p.m. All social distancing guidelines will be adhered to. The virtual ceremony will also air on FOX29/WUTV on Saturday, June 27th at 9 p.m. Students will receive detailed instructions and one entry for their family vehicle and accommodations have been made for a second parent not in the same household. Stay safe!

post_text: 13 Holland Central School seniors were honored by the Greater East Aurora Chamber of Commerce as Chamber's Choice honorees. These honorees exhibit a general concern for the well being of others, willing to go the extra mile, be involved in and demonstrate qualities of leadership in both school and community activities and demonstrate a strong work ethic. Holland students chosen were: Laura Anderson, Tyler Candler, Sarah Pawig, Sophie Schmidbauer, Sophia Serpas, Abigail Shafer, Madelyn Tavernier, Renee Wright, Haley Wylupski, David Zywiczynski and those who also attend Ormsby Educational Center: Jenna Dietz, Joseph Fishlock and Maddelyn Massucci. post_text: In honor of Citizen Science week, students in Mrs. Patterson's Living Environment classes have been busy doing science research online! In the first project, students looked at electron micrographs of cells to learn more about mitochondria. In the second project, ‚ÄúBashTheBug‚Äù, students helped Philip Fowler, a computational biophysicist and lead CRyPTIC researcher. This project asks participants to look at bacterial growth to determine if a particular sample of bacteria is resistant to antibiotics, and at what concentration of antibiotic the bacteria are killed. It‚Äôs a great extension of the bacteria lab completed in class.

post_text:
We know that there are critical blood shortages during this time. Before the school closure, The Connect Life Club at Holland HS took a field trip to the Connect Life facility on February 27th to learn what happens to the blood and organs that are donated. We were given a very thorough tour and treat several surprises.

The knowledgeable staff answered all of the student's questions and they capped off a successful trip with a special treat at Sweet Jenny's Candy and Ice Cream shop in Williamsville. The owner, Howard Cadmus, personally served the students, took pictures and gave our students a free gift to take home.

The HollandConnectLife Club is a ConnectLife-sponsored multi-disciplinary program that assists groups of students at area high schools in the planning, development, and implementation of a campaign to increase awareness about organ, tissue, and blood donation among their peers.

If you are able, please consider donating blood to help those in need.

post_text:
Students spent last week researching and designing sustainable houses for Mrs. Patterson's Applied Science class. Many students chose to design their final 3D model in Minecraft. Enjoy three great home examples here.

House 1: Here‚Äôs a beautiful house with multiple balconies, a pond, and a campfire. As the student who created the house was presenting on Zoom, another student joined him virtually on Minecraft, fished in the pond, and cooked his catch on the campfire!

The house had many beautiful rooms. Pictured is a bedroom with large windows to take advantage of natural light supplemented by solar powered LED lights.

House 2: This second house was built by a forest for protection from the elements and wood for supplemental heating. Students took advantage of the nearby creek and used it for power and water supply.

House #3: Amazon tree house with a large windmill

This tree house took full advantage of all the Amazon has to offer for renewable energy.

$100 Daily for Non-Certified Substitutes without a 4-year degree
$115 Daily for Non-Certified Substitutes with a 4-year degree
$125 Daily for Certified Substitutes

Substitute Bus Drivers are paid $17.00 per hour.

For more information please visit our website at https://www.hollandcsd.org/domain/7

post_text:
Dear Holland CSD Community,

A short message in these unusual times to let you all know how blessed I feel to be in such a wonderful, supportive, adaptive community. That community includes our neighbors, parents, students, extended families, teachers, administrators, supervisors, board of education and all of our support staff. While the landscape keeps changing amid the daunting tasks that lay before us your eagerness to teach, learn, work and communicate differently has made my leadership responsibilities less challenging. Please accept my humble gratitude for your cooperation, assistance and flexibility. My fervent hope is that we all return from this in good health with a thorough understanding that we are a team!!!!!

Stay safe,
Cathy Fabiatos
Superintendent of Schools

Two Important Reminders, One about Meals, One about Building Access:

Meals will only be provided on days when students would otherwise have been in school. This Friday, March 20th was a regularly scheduled Superintendent's Conference Day so there will be no meals provided. If families are in need of food for these days, they can contact

Boys & Girls Club of Holland
79 Vermont Street
Holland NY 14080
Monday - Friday
Hours: 8 a.m. - 4 p.m.

Rural Outreach Center (ROC)
730 Olean Road
East Aurora, NY 14052
Monday - Friday
Hours: 10 a.m. - 2 p.m.
They also suggested people visit their website for other services in our area at https://theroc.co/.

Additionally, if you need to access the building to retrieve things from your child's locker, call the main office of that building between 8am-3pm to schedule an appointment to pick those things up. You won't be allowed in the building, but a staff member will retrieve items for you. After 3pm on Thursday 3/19, you will NO LONGER be able to request such access.

post_text:
Good morning Holland Families.

First and foremost, your student‚Äôs safety is our number one concern.

Recognize that the current situation we find ourselves in is fluid and ever-changing.

Your students will be able to remove their personal items and empty all lockers and cubbies between the hours of 4 p.m. and 7:30 p.m. today, March 17, 2020, only. Bring a garbage bag, please. Building access will be controlled and only one individual per family will be allowed entrance.

ES parents will take home personal items and receive instructional materials for their students.

MS and HS students will remove personal items, clear lockers and be sure they have their computers and chargers.

Personal calls will be made to those who need to pick up medication.

Please refer to our website shortly for more detailed information.

Know that we will provide instruction, support and make a connection with each of our students throughout the shutdown.

Stay safe and thank you!!!!!

In accordance with the Erie County Executive recommendation that people avoid large gatherings of more than 50 people, and in light of the declaration of multiple States of Emergency, all Erie County school districts will be closed until April 20, 2020. During the week of April 13th we will reassess the actual return date.

Administrators and supervisors will finalize plans tomorrow. All Faculty and staff are expected to report on Tuesday. Details will follow.

post_text: The National Junior Honor Society (NJHS) is hosting a leprechaun chase on March 21, 2020 to raise money for cancer research. The race is open to all those in grades K-12. The event will take place on the high school track, with registration opening at 10 a.m. and the race starting at 10:30 a.m. Participants are encouraged to wear green! Bring the registration form and money to registration. The student in each school building who raises the most money for cancer research will win a $25 Regal gift card. If you have any questions, please contact Mrs. Elliott at delliott (@) hollandcsd (.) org or 716-537-8200 Ex 6208. Registration forms can be found at https://www.hollandcsd.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=1&ModuleInstanceID=5347&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=10876&PageID=1

post_text: Students in Mrs. Patterson's ECC Environmental Science class completed their mosquito research this month. DNA was isolated from local mosquitoes and Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) was used to amplify the sample. DNA was analyzed for Wolbachia infection using electrophoresis. Students successfully found that the locally collected Anopheles and Culosita mosquitoes were infected. This infection has been used to fight Zika virus worldwide, making student surveys of local mosquito populations of interest to scientists.

post_text: Mosquito research continues for the ECC Environmental Science class. Students learned clean technique (to keep their samples from being contaminated) as they extracted DNA from the locally caught mosquitoes they identified earlier this year. Students will analyze the amount of DNA they collected in preparation for further studies. Students will learn Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) next, to screen their mosquitoes for the presence of Wolbachia, an infection that has been used by genetic engineers to fight Dengue Fever, a mosquito-borne illness.

The eighth-graders recently took a field trip to the Ormsby Educational Center to learn about the programs that Erie 2-Chautauqua-Cattaraugus BOCES offers to high school students in Career & Technical Education. Students got to explore and learn more about the programs, such as Culinary Arts, Small/Large Animal Science and Sports Conditioning and Exercise Science. "I believe that the students really got something out of it and that some of our staff did as well, including myself", said Mr. Flood. "The Erie 2 Boces staff were very welcoming and introduced us to many career fields that some students didn‚Äôt know existed."

Students are able to attend a Career and Technical Education program in their junior and senior years of high school. This trip was intended to get students to start thinking about their future and the different options they can discover in high school.

On January 16th, Mr. Karches' social studies classes presented their Maya, Inca, and Aztec interdisciplinary project.
Students created a 3 min presentation as well as models and powerpoints to display their research on one aspect of an Inca, Mayan, or Aztec society. The project focus on the geography, religion, achievements, politics, economics, and social structure of the cultures. While students presented the information, other fifth-graders completed an intellectual scavenger hunt to locate key information about the different cultures.
In addition to the presentations, students displayed their Mayan, Inca, and Aztec myths they wrote and Illustrated in ELA classes. Students were also allowed to view the constellations projects created in Mrs. O'Malley's science class based on Mayan astrology and religious beliefs. Participants also had the opportunity to answer Mayan math questions for prizes. Everyone involved had a fantastic time and learned a lot about these 3 great civilizations.

post_text: Students in Mrs. Ginnitti's AP Art and Art 3 courses participated in the Memory Project again this year. It is a project that invites young artists to create portraits for children facing challenges in countries all over the world. This year, our portraits were created for 9 children in Nigeria who have been displaced by the Boko Haram insurgency. The intent of the portraits is to help the children feel valued and important, to know that many people care about their well being, and to act as meaningful pieces of personal history in the future. For art students who participate, the project is intended to be an opportunity to creatively practice kindness and global awareness. Please check out these incredible drawings.

post_text:
ECC Environmental Science students were busy before break, conducting experiments and doing research.

Students worked to prepare tubes for DNA mosquito research. Tubes will be used by the students to extract DNA out of local mosquitoes and screen them for Wolbachia infection. This infection has been used to fight Dengue Fever by scientific researchers. Student data will be compiled with other schools in the area to give scientists an idea of the scope of Wolbachia infection in Western NY and PA.

They also collected cloud and sun data for NASA. Data is compiled onto the GLOBE (Global Learning and Observations to Benefit the Environment) database. This international database is accessible by anyone and is designed to complement NASA satellite data with citizen science ground observations. If the students collected data during a satellite fly-over, NASA will automatically sends an email to their teacher so the class can verify the two measurements and comment on any discrepancies. Ground data collected by the students is a very valuable component to NASA's database.

If you have any questions, please feel free to contact us at cse-edweek@buffalo.edu.

Do you remember how difficult it was to choose your career when you were graduating high school? With numerous opportunities but little experience, it is very difficult for students to plan their future career.

We could use your help. If you would like to give a presentation (about 30 minutes in length) to high school students about your career, we would love to have your help! We run career presentations during lunch periods and students bring their lunch to the library to participate. Our lunch periods run 9:55-10:36, 10:40-11:21 and 11:25-12:06. You can choose your time or speak to all 3 groups if you like.

Just fill out the form linked below and email it to Lisa Hanlon- lhanlon@hollandcsd.org or call 537-8219.

post_text: Don't forget that tonight is the discussion on the future of our students in the workplace hosted by the Greater East Aurora Chamber of Commerce!
shared_text:
Holland Central Schools
October 17, 2019 at 12:55 PM ¬∑

On Wednesday, November 6 at 5:30 p.m., the Greater East Aurora Chamber of Commerce will be holding a discussion on the future of our students in the workplace. The discussion is intended to work to develop a better understanding of the workforce needs of the business community and partnerships in better preparing students for the workplace. Parents, students, teachers, school administrators and business leaders are all invited to participate in the discussion. The event will be held at 42 North, 25 Pine Street in East Aurora.

Topics will be wide-ranging including on employers most important needs and the challenges of opening the career door to students. To RSVP or more information, please contact the Greater East Aurora Chamber of Commerce at (716) 652-8444 or eanycc@verizon.net.

post_text: ECC Environmental Science students applied their knowledge of creek testing to our own East Branch Cazenovia Creek last week. They took samples for water temperature, pH, nitrates, transparency, dissolved oxygen, and macroinvertebrates. Their data will be uploaded on the GLOBE website (Global Learning and Observations to Benefit the Environment) and will be available internationally to scientists and citizens alike. Through the winter and spring months, students will analyze and compare their data collected on both streams to local and international data on the GLOBE website. They will prepare a scientific poster to be presented at a local or international (virtual) symposium.

post_text:
Holland Middle School hosted the annual Innovation Day on October 24, 2019. The day featured several local science and technology related businesses who visited the school to show students the different career possibilities there are in STEM fields. Each presenter also prepared a hands-on activity to allow students to explore more about the field.

This year, presenters from 10 different groups worked with students. Read more on our website: https://www.hollandcsd.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=1&ModuleInstanceID=5347&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=10542&PageID=1

Thank you to ASCE Buffalo Section, Linde North America, FeijenDesignBuild, University Pediatric Dentistry, Turner Construction Company, Erie 2-Chautauqua-Cattaraugus-BOCES, Astronics, Diversified Controls, Inc., Absolut Care, and Holland Volunteer Fire Department.
